    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What are the four DISC personality types?</summary>
        <p>The four DISC types are Dominance (D), which is direct and results-oriented; Influence (I), which is enthusiastic and people-oriented; Steadiness (S), which is patient and team-focused; and Conscientiousness (C), which is analytical and quality-driven. Most people are a blend of two or more types, with one or two being more prominent in their behavioral profile. You can discover your blend with our <a href="/test/disc-personality-test/">free DISC personality test</a>.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How accurate is the DISC assessment?</summary>
        <p>Well-constructed DISC instruments demonstrate good test-retest reliability and are considered reliable for understanding behavioral tendencies and communication styles. DISC measures observable behavior and communication preferences rather than deep personality traits, and it is most accurate when used for its intended purposes: improving communication, building team awareness, and enhancing workplace relationships. It should not be used as a sole hiring filter or to predict job performance in isolation.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can your DISC type change over time?</summary>
        <p>Your core DISC profile tends to remain relatively stable, as it reflects natural behavioral tendencies. However, people adapt their behavior in different contexts. You might display high Dominance at work but more Steadiness at home. Life experiences and personal development can also shift the emphasis within your profile over the years. DISC measures behavioral preferences, not fixed traits, so some variation is expected and healthy.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How is DISC different from the MBTI?</summary>
        <p>DISC focuses on observable behavior and communication styles, while MBTI focuses on cognitive preferences like how you perceive and process information. DISC uses four behavioral dimensions while MBTI uses four dichotomies producing 16 types. DISC is primarily used in workplace settings for team building and communication, while MBTI is used more broadly for personal development. Neither is inherently better; they measure different aspects of personality.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Should employers use DISC for hiring decisions?</summary>
        <p>DISC should not be the primary basis for hiring decisions. It was designed to improve communication and teamwork, not to predict job performance or screen candidates. Using DISC as a hiring filter can lead to biased decisions. However, DISC can be valuable during onboarding to help new hires understand team dynamics and can help managers adapt their leadership style to support different team members effectively.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

